    <h1>Biryani : My Most-Beloved Dish</h1>
    <img src="biryani.jpg"> 
    <p>Biryani is a mixed dish popular in South Asia, made with <strong>rice</strong> and <b>meat</b> of the consumer's choice. To cater to vegetarians, the meat can be substituted with <b>vegetables</b> or <b>paneer</b>.</p>
    
    <h2>Origins of Biryani</h2>
    <p>The origins of biryani can be traced back to ancient Persia <i>modern-day Iran</i>, where a similar dish called pulao or pilaf was prepared.</p>
    Another theory states that, biryani made it's way into India through the Mughal Empire, under the rule of King Babur.

    <h2>Types of Briyani</h2>
    <p>Biryani, a beloved and aromatic dish, is a flavorful celebration of spices, rice, and meat or vegetables. With roots across South Asia and the Middle East, biryani has evolved into many regional variations, each with its unique taste, preparation style, and cultural touch. From the rich Hyderabadi dum biryani to the fragrant Kolkata version, here's a look at the delicious types of biryani enjoyed around the world.</p>
